::: {.ud-text-sm .course-overview--component-margin--1nlYK .styles--description--33-vq purpose="course-description"}
## Description {#description .ud-heading-xl .styles--description__header--2Z7Vb purpose="description-title"}

::: show-more-module--container--2QPRN
[]{#show-more--467 data-type="checkbox" data-checked=""
style="display: none;"}

::: {.show-more-module--content--cjTh0 .show-more-module--with-gradient--1ZDrA style="max-height: 22.1rem;"}
::: {tabindex="-1"}
::: {purpose="safely-set-inner-html:description:description"}
Apache Airflow is an open-source  platform to programmatically author,
schedule and monitor workflows. If you have many ETL(s) to manage,
Airflow is a must-have.

In this course you are going to learn everything you need to start using
Apache Airflow through theory and pratical videos. Starting from very
basic notions such as, what is Airflow and how it works, we will dive
into advanced concepts such as, how to create plugins and make real
dynamic pipelines.
:::

::: {.styles--audience--2xuzW purpose="target-audience"}
## Who this course is for: {#who-this-course-is-for .ud-heading-xl .styles--audience__title--1qhlO}

-   People being curious about data engineering.
-   People who want to learn basic and advanced concepts about Apache
    Airflow.
-   People who like hands-on approach.
:::
:::
:::

## Instructor {#instructor .ud-heading-xl .styles--instructors__header--20N27}

::: {.instructor--instructor--2sjZy purpose="instructor-bio"}
[]{#instructor-1 .in-page-offset-anchor}

[Marc Lamberti](https://wdc.udemy.com/user/lockgfg/)

::: {.ud-text-sm .instructor--instructor__description--1s-Oo}
::: show-more-module--container--2QPRN

style="display: none;"}

::: {.show-more-module--content--cjTh0 .show-more-module--with-gradient--1ZDrA style="max-height: 14.6rem;"}
::: {tabindex="-1"}
::: {purpose="description-content"}
Hi there,

My name is Marc Lamberti, I\'m 27 years old and I\'m very happy to
arouse your curiosity! I\'m currently working as Big Data Engineer in
full-time for the biggest online bank in France, dealing with more than
1 500 000 clients. For more than 3 years now, I created different ETLs
in order to address the problems that a bank encounters everyday such
as, a platform to monitor the information system in real time to detect
anomalies and reduce the number of client\'s calls, a tool detecting  in
real time any suspicious transaction or potential fraudster, an ETL to
valorize massive amount of data into Cassandra and so on.

The biggest issue when you are a Big Data Engineer is to deal with the
growing number of available open source tools. You have to know how to
use them, when to use them and how they connect to each other in order
to build robust, secure and performing systems solving your underlying
business needs.

I strongly believe that the best way to learn and understand a new skill
is by taking a hands-on approach with just enough theory to explain the
concepts and a big dose of practice to be ready in a production
environment. That\'s why in each of my courses you will always find
practical examples associated with theoric explanations.

Have a great learning time!
:::

## 13. \[Practice\] Installing Apache Airflow {#launch-modal-title--576 .ud-sr-only}

::: {.section .lecture-view--container--pL22J aria-label="Section 2: Getting Started with Airflow, Lecture 13: [Practice] Installing Apache Airflow"}

\[Practice\] Installing Apache Airflow
:::

::: article-asset--container--3djM8
::: {.article-asset--content--1dAQ9 .rt-scaffolding purpose="safely-set-inner-html:rich-text-viewer:html"}
#### Installing Apache Airflow

\

Hi there 👋

It\'s time to install Apache Airflow. As you are going to see, it\'s
very simple.

\

**Prerequisites**

First, make sure you have installed Docker Desktop and Visual Studio. If
not, take a look at these links:

-   [Get Docker](https://docs.docker.com/get-docker/){target="_blank"
    rel="noopener noreferrer"}

-   [Get Visual Studio
    Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/download){target="_blank"
    rel="noopener noreferrer"}

Docker needs privilege rights to work, make sure you have them.

**Follow the documentation first.**\
If you have trouble to install these tools, here are some videos to help
you

-   [Install Docker on Windows
    10](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lIkxbE_We1I&ab_channel=JamesStormes){target="_blank"
    rel="noopener noreferrer"}

-   [Install Docker on Windows 10 with WSL
    2](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h0Lwtcje-Jo&ab_channel=BeachcastsProgrammingVideos){target="_blank"
    rel="noopener noreferrer"}

-   [Install Docker on Windows
    11](https://youtu.be/6k1CyA5zYgg?t=249){target="_blank"
    rel="noopener noreferrer"}

\

**Install Apache Airflow with Docker**

\

1.  Create a folder **materials** in your **Documents**

2.  In this folder, download the following file: [docker compose
    file](https://airflow.apache.org/docs/apache-airflow/2.5.1/docker-compose.yaml){target="_blank"
    rel="noopener noreferrer"}

3.  If you right-click on the file and save it, you will end up with
    docker-compose.yaml.txt. Remove the .txt and keep
    docker-compose.yaml

4.  Open your terminal or CMD and go into **Documents/materials**

5.  Open Visual Studio Code by typing the command: `code .`

6.  You should have something like this

    ![](./The%20Complete%20Hands-On%20Introduction%20to%20Apache%20Airflow%20_%20Udemy%20Business_files/2022-05-19_08-58-14-75ad4de4f9c3fa386546708ce86db04a.png){align="middle"}

7.  Right click below docker-compose.yml and create a new file `.env`
    (don\'t forget the dot before env)

8.  In this file add the following lines

    ::: ud-component--base-components--code-block
    <div>

    ``` {.prettyprint .linenums .prettyprinted role="presentation" style=""}
    AIRFLOW_IMAGE_NAME=apache/airflow:2.4.2AIRFLOW_UID=50000
    ```

    </div>
    :::

    and save the file

    ![](./The%20Complete%20Hands-On%20Introduction%20to%20Apache%20Airflow%20_%20Udemy%20Business_files/2022-05-19_08-58-15-94fb1fff7e92c0ca1378ec7421e0f650.png){align="middle"}

9.  Go at the top bar of Visual Studio Code -\> Terminal -\> New
    Terminal

    ![](./The%20Complete%20Hands-On%20Introduction%20to%20Apache%20Airflow%20_%20Udemy%20Business_files/2022-05-19_08-58-15-c82d370ca2d8cf4b8eecc5337650dca6.png){align="middle"}

10. In your new terminal at the bottom of Visual Studio Code, type the
    command `docker-compose up -d` and hit `ENTER`

    ![](./The%20Complete%20Hands-On%20Introduction%20to%20Apache%20Airflow%20_%20Udemy%20Business_files/2022-05-19_08-58-15-8a8428697d23ce89a6cd8af85881523c.png){align="middle"}

11. You will see many lines scrolled, wait until it\'s done. Docker is
    downloading Airflow to run it. It can take up to 5 mins depending on
    your connection. If Docker raises an error saying it can\'t download
    the docker image, ensure you are not behind a proxy/vpn or corporate
    network. You may need to use your personal connection to make it
    work. At the end, you should end up with something like this:

    ![](./The%20Complete%20Hands-On%20Introduction%20to%20Apache%20Airflow%20_%20Udemy%20Business_files/2022-05-19_08-58-15-1d0b2c401e8b14e1d23ec2024eaf0eef.png){align="middle"}

Well done, you\'ve just installed Apache Airflow with Docker! 🎉

\

Open your web browser and go to `localhost:8080`

![](./The%20Complete%20Hands-On%20Introduction%20to%20Apache%20Airflow%20_%20Udemy%20Business_files/2022-05-19_08-58-15-8e7bab039ef558f46a3263d851649e95.png){align="middle"}

#### Troubleshoots

-\> If you don\'t see this page, make sure you have nothing already
running on the port 8080

Also, go back to your terminal on Visual Studio Code and check your
application with `docker-compose ps`

All of your \"containers\" should be healthy as follow:

![](./The%20Complete%20Hands-On%20Introduction%20to%20Apache%20Airflow%20_%20Udemy%20Business_files/2022-05-19_08-58-15-414bbbd37e901753ea738f68380ef573.png){align="middle"}

If a container is not healthy. You can check the logs with
`docker logs materials_name_of_the_container`

Try to spot the error; once you fix it, restart Airflow with
`docker-compose down` then `docker-compose up -d`

and wait until your container states move from starting to healthy.

-\> If you see this error

![](./The%20Complete%20Hands-On%20Introduction%20to%20Apache%20Airflow%20_%20Udemy%20Business_files/2023-03-06_08-28-42-9884e885f01d16f91bd4a0f03ed267db.png){align="middle"}

remove your volumes with `docker volume prune` and run
`docker-compose up -d `again

-\> If you see that airflow-init docker container has exited, that\'s
normal :)

If you still have trouble, reach me on the Q/A with your error.
